        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A 60-year-old man with a long history of diabetes presents with visual disturbances, including difficulty seeing and floaters. Given his elevated blood glucose levels, which enzyme is most likely responsible for his eye manifestations?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q4021189",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30034,
      "difficulty_level": "difficult",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. D) Aldose reductase </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Aldose reductase</strong> is the key enzyme involved in the <strong>polyol pathway</strong>, where<strong> glucose </strong>is<strong> converted to sorbitol,</strong> and then <strong>sorbitol is</strong> converted<strong> to fructose. </strong>In the context of<strong> hyperglycemia,</strong> as seen in<strong> long-term diabetes</strong>, there is an <strong>increased flux of glucose</strong> through the<strong> polyol pathway. </strong>The <strong>accumulation of sorbitol in tissues </strong>that <strong>do not </strong>require<strong> insulin for glucose uptake</strong>, such as the <strong>lens, nerves,</strong> and<strong> blood vessels of the eye,</strong> can lead to<strong> osmotic stress and subsequent damage</strong>. This is a contributing factor to <strong>diabetic</strong> <strong>complications</strong> such as <strong>cataracts, retinopathy, and other microvascular complications</strong> that can <strong>affect vision.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">&nbsp;<u>Explanation: </u></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A. Hexokinase:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> Hexokinase catalyzes the<strong> phosphorylation of glucose to glucose-6-phosphate </strong>in most tissues and is <strong>not</strong> directly associated with the <strong>specific complications</strong> seen in the <strong>eyes due to diabetes.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B. Glucokinase:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>Glucokinase</strong> acts as a <strong>glucose sensor </strong>in the <strong>pancreas and liver</strong>, catalyzing the<strong> phosphorylation of glucose </strong>to <strong>glucose-6-phosphate</strong>. It is <strong>not</strong> directly linked to the pathogenesis of <strong>diabetic eye complications.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C. Sorbitol dehydrogenase:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> While <strong>sorbitol dehydrogenase </strong>is involved in the <strong>conversion of sorbitol to fructose</strong> in the <strong>polyol</strong> pathway, it is the accumulation of<strong> sorbitol </strong>due to the action of <strong>aldose reductase</strong> that is primarily responsible for the<strong> osmotic damage</strong> seen in<strong> diabetic complications of the eye.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Glucose</strong> can enter the <strong>lens of the eye </strong>and get <strong>converted to Sorbitol </strong>with the help of <strong>aldose reductase. </strong>This enzyme is a major contributor to<strong> diabetic complication </strong>due to<strong> accumulation of sorbitol </strong>which is <strong>hygroscopic sugar </strong>and causes<strong> swelling of the eye </strong>in <strong>untreated diabetic patients</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Harper 30/e:&nbsp; p 205; Vasudevan 9/e: 135.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
